      {
        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "If we consider only *transition metal ions*, then **Cu²⁺** holds the crown with **1,951 distinct ligands**. Copper(II) is renowned for its versatile coordination chemistry — it readily forms stable complexes with N-, O-, and S-donor ligands — which explains why it has been so extensively studied. The rest of the top 5 transition metals (Ni²⁺, Zn²⁺, Co²⁺, Cd²⁺) are all divalent ions of the Irving–Williams series, consistent with the well-known trend that these ions are the most commonly studied in stability-constant work.",
